{"author":{"id":"8bc937586ce27bae75be934f2d5147d1783ed8988a9d4a9dc9b83ef3b5d4bb1c"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1706215962,"nonce":"CYpNqV6I8mk7ort9zDfuE3cGuGk=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOAW4Y0s59PQF2","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/5734","origin":"github"},"title":"raxml output missing when classifying environmental sequences","message":"The raxml tool is mostly used for inferring phylogenies, and the outputs of the wrapper are geared towards that purpose, it seems. However, with setting `-f v`, other output is produced, but these don't show up in the history. This is a bit unfortunate, as the option of classifying environmental sequences is very useful for metabarcoding studies. It would therefore be wonderful if this could be addressed.\n\nHow to reproduce on a Galaxy server:\n\n- upload the provided [FASTA file](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/files/14057573/raxml-ready.fa.txt)\n- upload the provided [Newick file](https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/files/14057595/raxml-ready.tre.txt)\n- choose the raxml tool\n- `Source file`: select the FASTA file from the history\n- `Model type`: `nucleotide`, and `GTRCAT`\n- `Full option list` =\u003e `Algorithm to execute` =\u003e `Classify Environmental Sequences (v)`\n- `Binary constraint tree`: select the Newick file from history\n\nWhen launching this job, it runs to completion, and everything turns green - but most of the outputs are zero bytes. Only the STDOUT info file has contents showing that it worked but that it produced files with extensions that the wrapper doesn't appear to expect. Hence, those are absent from the outputs, although they appear to exist on the server. The `RAxML_labelledTree.galaxy` would be most interesting to have, but the others would be great, too.\n\nBelow is reproduced the info output that shows (at the bottom) what files were produced:\n\n```\nIMPORTANT WARNING: Alignment column 1 contains only undetermined values which will be treated as missing data\n\nIMPORTANT WARNING\nFound 1 column that contains only undetermined values which will be treated as missing data.\nNormally these columns should be excluded from the analysis.\n\nAn alignment file with undetermined columns removed has already\nbeen printed to file /data/files/9/8/6/dataset_986841c4-24f4-4380-bb96-8978f1c673b2.dat.reduced\n\n\nUsing BFGS method to optimize GTR rate parameters, to disable this specify \"--no-bfgs\" \n\n\nAlignment has 1 completely undetermined sites that will be automatically removed from the input data\n\nFound a total of 7 taxa in tree file /data/files/6/7/9/dataset_6794901d-d9e6-4fbe-a33c-57ac458aaaa1.dat\n\n\nThis is RAxML version 8.2.12 released by Alexandros Stamatakis on May 2018.\n\nWith greatly appreciated code contributions by:\nAndre Aberer      (HITS)\nSimon Berger      (HITS)\nAlexey Kozlov     (HITS)\nKassian Kobert    (HITS)\nDavid Dao         (KIT and HITS)\nSarah Lutteropp   (KIT and HITS)\nNick Pattengale   (Sandia)\nWayne Pfeiffer    (SDSC)\nAkifumi S. Tanabe (NRIFS)\nCharlie Taylor    (UF)\n\n\nAlignment has 65 distinct alignment patterns\n\nProportion of gaps and completely undetermined characters in this alignment: 0.17%\n\nRAxML likelihood-based placement algorithm\n\nUsing 1 distinct models/data partitions with joint branch length optimization\n\n\nAll free model parameters will be estimated by RAxML\nML estimate of 25 per site rate categories\n\nPartition: 0\nAlignment Patterns: 65\nName: No Name Provided\nDataType: DNA\nSubstitution Matrix: GTR\n\n\n\n\nRAxML was called as follows:\n\nraxmlHPC-PTHREADS -T 3 -s /data/files/9/8/6/dataset_986841c4-24f4-4380-bb96-8978f1c673b2.dat -n galaxy -m GTRCAT -p 1234567890 -N 1 -B 0.03 -c 25 -f v -K GTR -r /data/files/6/7/9/dataset_6794901d-d9e6-4fbe-a33c-57ac458aaaa1.dat -W 100 \n\n\nRAxML placement algorithm: You provided a reference tree with 7 taxa; alignmnet has 8 taxa\n1 query taxa will be placed using maximum likelihood\n\nRAxML Evolutionary Placement Algorithm\n\nLikelihood of reference tree: -1267.304019\n\nRAxML will place 1 Query Sequences into the 11 branches of the reference tree with 7 taxa\n\nOverall Classification time: 0.041132\n\n\n\nLabelled reference tree including branch labels and query sequences written to file: /data/galaxy/jobs/031/31779/working/RAxML_labelledTree.galaxy\n\nLabelled reference tree with branch labels (without query sequences) written to file: /data/galaxy/jobs/031/31779/working/RAxML_originalLabelledTree.galaxy\n\nLabelled reference tree with branch labels in portable pplacer/EPA format (without query sequences) written to file: /data/galaxy/jobs/031/31779/working/RAxML_portableTree.galaxy.jplace\n\nClassification result file written to file: /data/galaxy/jobs/031/31779/working/RAxML_classification.galaxy\n\nClassification result file using likelihood weights written to file: /data/galaxy/jobs/031/31779/working/RAxML_classificationLikelihoodWeights.galaxy\n\nClassification entropy result file using likelihood weights written to file: /data/galaxy/jobs/031/31779/working/RAxML_entropy.galaxy\n\n```","files":null}]}